docs.abstract: How a genre writer has transformed book publishing.
docs.snippet: How a genre writer has transformed book publishing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Like most authors, James Patterson started out with one book, released in 1976, that he struggled to get published. It sold about 10,000 copies, a modest, if respectable, showing for a first novel. Last year, an estimated 14 million copies of his books in 38 different languages found their way onto beach blankets, airplanes and nightstands around the world. Patterson may lack the name recognition of a Stephen King, a John Grisham or a Dan Brown, but he outsells them all. Really, it’s not even close. (According to Nielsen BookScan, Grisham’s, King’s and Brown’s combined U.S. sales in recent years still don’t match Patterson’s.) This is partly because Patterson is so prolific: with the help of his stable of co-authors, he published nine original hardcover books in 2009 and will publish at least nine more in 2010.

docs.abstract: Evelyn Y. Davis, the corporate shareholder activist, and James E. Patterson, a retired government official, were married on Wednesday in Arlington, Va. Gerald E. Williams, a lawyer and Virginia civil magistrate, performed the ceremony in his office.    Ms. Davis, 76, is keeping her name. She is the editor of Highlights and Lowlights, a financial newsletter in Washington. She is the daughter of the late Marianne de Jong, who lived in Amsterdam, and the late Dr. Herman H. de Jong, who lived in Catonsville, Md.

docs.lead_paragraph: Eager fans of the author James Patterson will have to look in their mailboxes for the earliest access to his next book. At the Frankfurt Book Fair yesterday, Bertelsmann, the German publisher, announced that members of its book clubs would have the chance to get Mr. Patterson's next novel, "Honeymoon," (Warner Books) at least one month before it is available in retail stores. Members of the Book-of-the-Month Club in the United States, which is co-owned by Bertelsmann and Time-Warner, and other Bertelsmann-related clubs around the world can order the book for delivery in January. The thriller, about a woman whose husbands die mysteriously, is scheduled to go on sale in stores in the United States in February. EDWARD WYATT
